A Better Year for Migrants?
DUBLIN – Two major lessons emerge from the migration crisis in the Mediterranean.
First, Europe and the international community apply a cruelly ill-suited system for protecting the most vulnerable migrants.
Second, in the face of this system's ineffectiveness, populist actors continue to exploit fears to gain political support, undermining liberal and tolerant societies that required some 70 years of determined effort to construct.
This is why it is essential that this year there be undertaken a truly active approach at both European and global levels.
In September, UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon will convene an extraordinary summit aimed at building a robust global protection system for the most vulnerable migrants and refugees.
Let us hope that states will be ready to engage concretely and sustainably.
Necessary engagement has tragically been lacking throughout 2015.
In fact, had the international community provided even minimal support to the frontline countries – Turkey, Lebanon, and Jordan – which together host over four million refugees, the severity of last year’s crisis could have been significantly mitigated.
With around 10 billion euros, these countries would have been better equipped to house, feed, and educate refugees, thereby reducing the temptation to flee to Europe.
This failure could cost Germany alone up to 21 billion euros annually in the years to come.
But the financial implications of the crisis are beyond comparison with its human and political costs.
More than a million people risked their lives last year crossing the Mediterranean, enduring a exhausting journey through the Balkans thereafter.
Nearly 4,000 migrants lost their lives in the process, with many European countries turning their backs on the survivors by refusing to offer them asylum.
The most cynical political actors mercilessly exploited citizens' fears, promoting an odious nationalist narrative either by ignoring or distorting the migrant experience.
In the United States, for example, not a single one of the 780,000 refugees installed since September 11, 2001, has committed any terrorist act.
At the same time, immigrants generally pay more in taxes than they receive in social benefits.
And yet, extremist parties are dangerously flirting with taking political power in certain European countries, and are currently gaining support within bastions of liberalism that were previously solid.
Anti-immigration parties are already in power in Hungary and Poland.
Their success also leads traditional parties to promote an immigration-hostile policy themselves.
This situation has considerably damaged European cooperation.
The EU program aimed at caring for the million of refugees who arrived on its shores has only allowed for the "relocation" of 190.
Border controls have been reinstated in the territories of six Schengen-area countries, at least provisionally.
To the rest of the world, the EU now appears chauvinistic and incompetent.
Of course, resolving this crisis is not just about Europe; responsibility cannot be defined solely by geographical proximity.
Nevertheless, the EU today likely faces a threat to its very existence, which it can overcome only by demonstrating its capacity for solidarity and international leadership.
This is why it is up to member states to take the initiative by proposing solutions.
The highest priority is to establish legal and secure pathways for refugees to reach Europe.
This is not to say that every migrant in difficulty should be welcomed.
It nonetheless falls to the EU to be more systematically generous in its determination of the number of refugees to welcome, and to use organized mechanisms to facilitate their entry.
<s>Un tel système permettrait de protéger les migrants tout en sauvegardant l'Europe (grâce à la possibilité d'examiner pleinement les demandes).
<s>Au-delà d'une démarche visant à dissuader les demandeurs d'asile de risquer leur vie en traversant la Méditerranée, une telle approche permettrait de projeter une image de solidarité auprès des pays en première ligne, qui continuent d'abriter la majorité des réfugiés.
<s>Aspect tout aussi important, cette approche encouragerait le reste de la communauté internationale à contribuer aux efforts.
<s>Ceci nous conduit à la deuxième priorité de l'année 2016 : bâtir un solide système mondial de protection des réfugiés et migrants vulnérables.
<s>Cet objectif exigera avant tout que davantage de pays acceptent d'accueillir des réfugiés.
<s>Ces dernières années, l'Agence des Nations Unies pour les réfugiés est seulement parvenue à réinstaller moins de 75 000 des quelque 20 millions de réfugiés annuels.
<s>Plusieurs millions d'entre eux finissent dans une situation de migration prolongée, d'une durée moyenne estimée à 25 ans, prisonniers d'une sorte de purgatoire et incertains quant au jour d'un éventuel retour au pays.
<s>En 2016, il est nécessaire que les pays développés consentent à accueillir chaque année un nombre cumulé proche du million de réfugiés, soit via leur réinstallation, soit en leur accordant un visa humanitaire, étudiant, professionnel ou autre.
<s>Le Canada ayant affirmé qu'il accueillerait à lui seul 50 000 réfugiés syriens cette année, il s'agit d'un objectif clairement réalisable.
<s>Dans le même temps, la communauté internationale devra appuyer l'intégration de réfugiés dans d'importants pays d'accueil tels que la Turquie, le Kenya, le Liban et la Jordanie.
<s>In the current state, these countries are only receiving a fraction of the $3,000 to $5,000 annually needed for each refugee for housing, food, healthcare, education, and vocational training during the first few years of resettlement.
<s>These figures do not account for the necessary costs of constructing or upgrading infrastructure.
<s>For example, in Lebanon, the water supply systems are strained by the massive influx of refugees.
<s>In exchange for funding, these host countries could commit to fully integrating refugees into their schools, labor market, and civic institutions.
<s>However, effective integration of migrants will only be possible if countries in Europe and elsewhere rid themselves of their prejudices against migrants.
If these migrants remain considered as a burden, or even a security threat, reactionary political forces will continue to gain ground, depriving newcomers of opportunities and transforming fear into a self-fulfilling prophecy.
On the other hand, if welcoming states manage to integrate migrants with enthusiasm, everyone will benefit – including these countries (notably through remittances).
Last month, in Paris, the international community proved it was capable of subordinating national interests to a broader global objective: the fight against climate change.
In 2016, a similar effort is needed to build a better system of protection for migrants.
This is a matter of life or death for some 20 million refugees, for several million other vulnerable migrants – as well as a profound test of the civic health of democratic societies worldwide.
